05773nam a22009615i 9780812206418DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20122012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979904887  a97808122064187 a10.9783/97808122064182doi  a(DE-B1597)449542  a(OCoLC)794700783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ513b.K37 2012eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a306.84 12231 aKarras, Ruth Mazo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnmarriages :bWomen, Men, and Sexual Unions in the Middle Ages /cRuth Mazo Karras. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Marriage and Other Unions -- tChapter 1. The Church and the Regulation of Unions between Women and Men -- tChapter 2. Unequal Unions -- tChapter 3. Priests and Their Partners -- tChapter 4. On the Margins of Marriage -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Middle Ages are often viewed as a repository of tradition, yet what we think of as traditional marriage was far from the only available alternative to the single state in medieval Europe. Many people lived together in long-term, quasimarital heterosexual relationships, unable to marry if one was in holy orders or if the partners were of different religions. Social norms militated against the marriage of master to slave or between individuals of very different classes, or when the couple was so poor that they could not establish an independent household. Such unions, where the protections that medieval law furnished to wives (and their children) were absent, were fraught with danger for women in particular, but they also provided a degree of flexibility and demonstrate the adaptability of social customs in the face of slowly changing religious doctrine.Unmarriages draws on a wide range of sources from across Europe and the entire medieval millennium in order to investigate structures and relations that medieval authors and record keepers did not address directly, either in order to minimize them or because they were so common as not to be worth mentioning. Ruth Mazo Karras pays particular attention to the ways women and men experienced forms of opposite-sex union differently and to the implications for power relations between the genders. She treats legal and theological discussions that applied to all of Europe and presents a vivid series of case studies of how unions operated in specific circumstances to illustrate concretely what we can conclude, how far we can speculate, and what we can never know.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHISTORYxMedieval. 0aMan-woman relationshipszEuropexHistoryxTo 1500. 0aMan-woman relationshipszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMarriage (Canon law)xHistoryxTo 1500. 0aMarriage (Canon law)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMarriagezEuropexHistoryxTo 1500. 0aMarriagezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMate selectionzEuropexHistoryxTo 1500. 0aMate selectionzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aUnmarried couples (Canon law)xHistoryxTo 1500. 0aUnmarried couples (Canon law)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aUnmarried couplesxEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aUnmarried coupleszEuropexHistoryxTo 1500. 0aUnmarried coupleszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aGender Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aGender Studies.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWomen's Studies.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is